n of how constellations of knowledge and power produce and shape subjects, and in the last phase of his life, he became especially interested not only in how subjects are formed by these forces, but in how they ethically constitute themselves. In this lecture series and accompanying seminar, Foucault focuses on antiquity, starting with classical Greece, the early Roman Empire, and concluding with Christian monasticism in the fourth and fifth centuries AD. Foucault traces the development of a new kind of verbal practice—“speaking the truth about oneself”—in which the subject increasingly comes to be defined by its inner thoughts and desires. He deemed this new form of “hermeneutical” subjectivity important not just for historical reasons but also due to its enduring significance in modern society. Is another form of the self possible today?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHermeneutics. 0aSelf (Philosophy) 0aSelf (Philosophy). 0aSubject (Philosophy) 0aSubject (Philosophy). 0aSubjectivity. 0aTruth. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aFoucault, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFruchaud, Henri-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFruchaud, Henri-Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLorenzini, Daniele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenzini, Daniele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWyche, Daniel Louis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226623054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226623054/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyte